      <!-- ================================================ -->
      <!-- LORE — accordion                                 -->
      <!-- ================================================ -->
      <section id="lore" class="lore">
        <div class="container-default">
          <div class="lore-head">
            <div class="eyebrow metallic">the world, in seven pieces</div>
            <div class="rule" aria-hidden="true">
              <span class="rule-glyph metallic">✦</span>
            </div>
            <h2>The province in 4E&nbsp;191</h2>
            <p>
              Written in-world. Treat anything here as rumour, hearsay, or
              common knowledge you might have overheard on the road.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="lore-accordion">
            <details class="lore-entry" open>
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">I</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The White-Gold Concordat: A Betrayal of Skyrim</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>The Great War ended in 4E 175. The Empire agreed to ban the worship of Talos across all its provinces. In Skyrim, the office of High Kingship was dissolved. The Jarls now answer to Imperial authority directly, with no native head of state to buffer them.</p>
                <p>The year is 4E 191. The soldiers who bled at the Red Ring came home to find their patron god illegal and their King's law abolished by the stroke of a pen. The Empire will tell you it had no choice. The ink is sixteen years dry. But the argument is not.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">II</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The Cloak, The Prisoner, and The Trial</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>Ask ten Nords about Ulfric Stormcloak and you will get ten different answers. Some say he is the last true Voice of Skyrim, a man who trained his voice like a weapon and refused to let the Concordat stand unopposed. Others say he is a fool and a dead man. Defying the Aldmeri would have gotten thousands killed for a war nobody could win.</p>
                <p>It is the month of Frostfall. He is a prisoner in an Imperial cell, waiting for a fate nobody but the Emperor will decide. The question of what happens to him is the only thing keeping Eastmarch and Windhelm from open rebellion. If he's tried and executed, Skyrim's Sons have a martyr. The Nine Holds hold their collective breath.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">III</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The Imperial Garrison: Veterans of Foreign Wars</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>The soldiers garrisoning Skyrim in 4E 191 are not the Fourth Legion, coming decades later, with Tullius. These men came home from the Great War to a disbanded High King and a province that does not entirely want them here, enforcing a Concordat most of them find as distasteful as the Nords do.</p>
                <p>They do not enforce the Talos ban. Not actively. They look the other way, and the Thalmor know it. Nobody says anything about it, because the alternative is a question that many find impossible: when the swords get drawn, do you pick your God, your Homeland, or your Empire? Ask them why they stay. I believe it's a question worth asking any that you meet.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">IV</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The Thalmor: A Shadow on the Sky</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>The Thalmor have yet to set foot in Skyrim. But that's all about to change. The Emperor is aging, his heir not apparent. His only relative is his cousin, the lady Vici. Neither have been seen in a month.</p>
                <p>Their longest ambition is the restoration of Elvish supremacy across Tamriel. They believe the Empire is a structure that has already failed. Their work is to ensure that when it collapses, the Dominion fills the space it leaves. Every shrine burned is a log on the Empire's funeral pyre. A province full of people who hate their Empire is a province that will not rally to defend it. They are a dagger, held beneath the negotiating table. And they have the Jarl of Eastmarch upon the face of it.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">V</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The College of Winterhold: Magic and Misunderstanding</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>69 years ago, disaster struck the face of Winterhold off the side of a cliff, and it tumbled into the Sea of Ghosts. The College still stands. The shell of the city beneath it still blames it for the Collapse.</p>
                <p>Under the Concordat, the Dominion has a particular interest in controlling who practices magic. The College has received no end of threats, blackmail, and legal orders to quarter a Justiciar. They have, heretofore, refused. But this is growing harder each passing day. The Thalmor's Ambassador is coming. Whether the College survives the next years with its independence intact is a question its enemies, faculty, patron, and students will all come to decide.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">VI</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The Eight Divines and The Man</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>Eight Divines are openly recognized across the Empire. The Ninth is Talos, once called Tiber Septim, raised to godhood upon his death. Praying at one of his altars is now met with a noose. The Dominion denies his divinity ever existed. To them, he was a man, a conqueror, a dangerous delusion.</p>
                <p>To a Nord, he is the God who sat Shor's empty throne and proved that men could rise above their station. The altar in the temples of the Eight Divines lays empty. But the Temple of Talos in Windhelm has not officially closed. The Thalmor are watching. The Garrison holds them back, if only tentatively.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="lore-entry">
              <summary class="lore-entry-head">
                <span class="lore-numeral" aria-hidden="true">VII</span>
                <span class="lore-entry-title">The Holds</span>
                <svg class="lore-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                  <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <div class="lore-entry-body">
                <p>
                  Nine holds, nine seats of power, nine unique resources. Every
                  Jarl and every Steward is an original character held by a
                  vetted player. From Haafingar's port trade to The Reach's
                  silver to Winterhold's arcane components, the map is wired
                  for commerce, rivalry, and slow political pressure. Staff
                  seed the leadership. The players run everything else.
                </p>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

